The most basal group of temnospondyls is the superfamily Edopoidea. Edopoids have several primitive or plesiomorphic features, including a single occipital condyle and a bone called the intertemporal that is absent in other temnospondyls. Edopoids include the Late Carboniferous genus Edops and the family Cochleosauridae. Dendrerpetontidae has also been included in Edopoidea, and is the oldest known temnospondyl family. Balanerpeton woodi is the oldest species, having been present over 330 million years ago during the Early Carboniferous. It shares some features with the earliest temnospondyl, Eryops. Most species lived during the Late Permian and Early Triassic, but a recent study suggests that Cochleosaurus rineii was actually a fossilized giant of the Carboniferous. Dendrerpetontidae has also been cited as a member of Edopoidea, but an analysis based on phylogenetics of cranial structures suggests this is incorrect and that it is closer to Seymouriamorpha.

Originally, temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae. Early forms, with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements, were placed in the suborder Rachitomi, and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli. With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous forms has become artificial : for instance, Lungliosaurus tenuispidopsis, a lungless stereospondyl from the Lower Triassic of Argentina, has vertebrae like those of all other rhachitomous temnospondyls. The distinction between vertebral types is now recognized as an exclusively functional distinction which does not reflect convergent evolution ; Stereospondyli and Rachitomi are not considered to be sister groups.
